                  <p>
                    <h4>It’s The Quality That Matters</h4>
                    <br>Value Based Payment programs are not very old to US healthcare industry. These programs focus more on the value which the patients get out of their doctors’ visit rather than how much more patients a doctor examines.
                  <br><br>To explain this phenomenon in an equation:

                  <br> <h4>Value = Quality Measures + Patient Experience + Cost of care</h4>

                  <br> This explains in a way that if a patient visits the doctor then what are the quality measures through which the patient has been going through, what is the cost of treatment the responsible persons have to bear and if someone asks about the patient’s feedback then what is it?
                  <br>  In old orthodox way of care giving to patients the more the number of treatments or procedures the better was the quality of the services, but this approach is rapidly changing now as quality is more relying on the results or the right type of care rather than numbers.
                    Center for Medicare & Medicaid Services provided with four types of VBP and that pretty much covers all the important aspects of healthcare services to serve three parts aim that comprises of better care of individuals, better health for populations and lower cost.
                  <br>  Now these elements refer to the transition from fee for service to fee for performance. In value based approach the care strategies are developed around the patients. The providers, hospitals and primary care facilities join and integrate together in a way that they render their best services to help patients.
                    Without explaining more and adding general description, following are the programs which have been developed by center of Medicare and Medicaid:
                  <br><br> <b> APMs: Alternative Payment Models:</b><br>
                    It’s a payment method that gives added incentive payments to provide high-quality and cost-efficient care. APMs can apply to a specific clinical condition, a care episode, or a population.
                  <br>   Advanced APMs are a subcategory of APMs, and let practices earn more for taking on some risk related to their patients' results. You may earn a 5% incentive payment by going further in improving patient care and taking on risk through an Advanced APM.
                  <br>  <br>    <b> ESRD-QIP: End-Stage Renal Disease Quality Incentive Program:</b>
                  <br>  This program rewards outpatient dialysis or ESRD facilities treating patients with ESRD with incentive payments for the quality of care they give to people with Medicare. The program also lessens payments to ESRD facilities that don’t meet or beat certain performance criteria.
                  <br><br><br>
                    <b>HACRP: Hospital- Acquired Condition Reduction Program:</b><br>
                  <br>  This program motivates hospitals to improve patient safety and minimize the number of hospital-acquired situations, like pressure wounds and hip fractures after surgery.
                  <br>  This program saves Medicare hundreds of million dollars each year. These savings come from reducing what we pay to hospitals that rank worst among other hospitals for how often their patients get hospital-acquired illnesses.
                  <br><br> <b> HRRP: Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program:</b><br>
                  <br>  It enhances health care for people with Medicare by connecting what we pay hospitals to the quality of the care they deliver and not just quantity of the services they provide in a given performance tenure.
                  <br>  A hospital readmission occurs when a patient is admitted to a hospital within a specified time period after being discharged from an earlier initial hospitalization. For Medicare, 30 days’ time period is the specified time, and includes readmissions to any hospital, not just where the patient was initially hospitalized. It doesn’t include certain prearranged readmissions.
                  <br>  This program provides financial aid to hospitals to decrease costly and needless hospital readmissions. Hospitals can reduce readmissions by improved coordinating changes of care and enhancing the quality of care given to patients with Medicare.
                  <br><br> <b> HVBP: Hospital Value Based Purchasing Program:</b><br>
                  <br>  It rewards critical care hospitals with incentive payments for the quality of care they give to people with Medicare. This program supports improved clinical results for inpatients and makes their care experience better during hospital stays.
                  <br>  We pay participating hospitals for inpatient critical care services based on the quality of care, not just quantity of the services they provide in a given performance period.
                  <br><br>   <b> MIPS: Merit Based Incentive Payment System:</b><br>
                  <br>  This is a new payment system that will deliver annual updates to physicians starting in 2019, based on performance in four categories: quality, resource use, clinical practice improvement activities and meaningful use of an electronic health record system. This new system will adjust payments based on individual performance.
                  <br><br>   <b> VM: Value Modifier or Physician Value Based Modifier (PVBM):</b><br>
                  <br>   This program provides incentives to the providers based upon their quality of services compared to the cost of the services during a set time period for performance. These incentives are in the form of adjustments in the Physician Fee Schedule of Medicare.
                    <br>Lowering costs and increasing quality are the factors which contribute for rewards in VM.
                  <br><br>
                    <b>SNFVBP: Skilled Nursing Facility Value Based Purchasing Program:</b><br>
                  <br>  Skilled nursing facilities will get incentive payments if they provide quality care to the people with Medicare. This programs starts in 2019 and focuses on improved results for patients. This also emphasizes to make improved stay of patients in the facilities. The payment will be given to the facilities for their quality not the quantity.
                  <br>  It’s easily understandable by the names and description of programs that these approaches are diverting the care towards quality nor the quantity.
                  <br> These programs are supporting the overall healthcare industry in different ways but there are some challenges which are also being faced:
                  <br> More than 60% of family physicians have contracts with numerous payers and these providers are responsible for the quality measures required by each payer so it is observed that normally these quality measures do not line up and they also often use different specification for similar measure topic. Due to this factor the practices face administrative burden and complexities.
                  <br> There is a barrier in value based care delivery because of lack of alignment that creates variation. Creating integrated measures will reduce this variation and it will lead to reduction of burden on family physicians and quality will eventually improve. As mentioned earlier in this topic:
                    <br><br><b>‘The providers, hospitals and primary care facilities join and integrate together in a way that they render their best services to help patients’</b>




